The Americas
------------
[4] Mexico (City)
Date: Fri 22 Jul 2011
Source: Latin American Herald Tribune [edited]
http://www.laht.com/article.asp?ArticleId=408968&CategoryId=14091


The 1st measles case since 2007 has been reported in Mexico, and the
patient is an 18-month-old French girl, Health Secretary Jose Angel
Cordova said. The girl arrived in Mexico City on a flight from Paris
in the past few days, and health officials are trying to locate the
other passengers who were aboard the plane, Cordova said.

"The patient is an unvaccinated French girl, one-year-and-6-months
old, (who) arrived in our country. A positive diagnosis has already
been made, and ... a health cordon is being established," the health
secretary said.

The last case of a Mexican infected with measles was reported in
2004, and a foreigner was diagnosed with the disease in Mexico in
2007, according to a Health Secretariat spokesman.

"The most complicated thing" is finding those who had contact on the
plane "because (the girl) certainly may have been infected there,"
Cordova said, adding that he learned about the case only on Wednesday
[20 Jul 2011]. Health officials were prepared to handle a situation
like this and "we are seeing that there has been an important rise (in
the number of cases), particularly in Europe, (while) in the United
States, the majority (of measles cases) are not autochthonous, but it
is the same because of the movements (of people) that you have," the
health secretary said.

A health cordon is in place at the Mexico City airport, and people
traveling to the United States and Europe will be vaccinated, Cordova
said. Health officials are monitoring 7 other airports in Mexico, the
health secretary said.

--
